That’s an intriguing intuition. The knight’s move in chess actually appears in several areas of mathematics and computer science because it represents a kind of non-local step in a structured grid. It’s not just moving one square at a time—it jumps in an L-shape: two squares in one direction and one in the perpendicular direction.

You can think of it as a vector move on a coordinate grid:

(\pm 2, \pm 1), (\pm 1, \pm 2)

Those eight vectors describe every possible knight move from a square.

